---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const baseUrl = 'https://icontree.cosmoscope.workers.dev';

const promptText = `# IconTree Integration

Integrate IconTree Lottie icons into an EXISTING app.

## Target
Framework: [React / Flutter / React Native / etc.]
Component: [component name]
Lottie library: [lottie-react, lottie_flutter, etc.]
Local icon path: [e.g. src/assets/icons]

## Rules
- Integrate into the existing UI only.
- Do NOT create an icon library, gallery, marketplace, search page, or new design system.
- Reuse existing components, spacing, colors, theme, and naming.
- Output only the required code.
- No README, boilerplate, explanations, or unrelated files.
- IconTree provides ONLY Lottie (.json). Never use SVG.

## Design-time icon selection (AI only)
Base URL:
${baseUrl}

Search:
GET /icon/search?q=<query>&category=<optional>&page=<optional>&pageSize=<optional>

Response:
{
  "results": [
    { "url": "/path/icon.json" }
  ]
}

Workflow:
1. Search.
2. Pick the best icon.
3. Download:
   ${baseUrl}{url}
4. Bundle the JSON locally.
5. Final code must use the local asset only.

Do NOT ship search requests in the app.

If the user explicitly asks for an in-app icon picker/search UI, ask for confirmation because that is a different feature.

## Runtime (production)
- Import the local JSON.
- Render using the existing Lottie library.
- No network requests.
- No dynamic fetching.

## Theme / Icon Color
IconTree icons ship with a fixed fill color baked into the Lottie JSON (often white or black) that does NOT match the app theme.

You have two options:

1. Server-side recolor (recommended — simplest, no runtime color code):
   When downloading the icon at design time, append a hex color to the fetch URL:
   GET {baseUrl}/icon/use/<iconname>.json?color=<hex>
   Example: {baseUrl}/icon/use/arrow-right-bold.json?color=%23ff0000  (URL-encode the leading # as %23)
   The returned JSON already has its fill/stroke recolored — bundle THAT file locally and use it in production.

2. Runtime recolor in the app, using the platform's Lottie color override method (dynamic properties, color filters, or JSON preprocessing that swaps fill/stroke values). Use this only if the app must recolor at runtime.

Icons must follow the app's light/dark theme. Prefer option 1 and bundle a per-theme colored JSON (e.g. one light, one dark) or recolor once per theme.

## Component requirements
- Follow existing architecture.
- Keep size, loop, autoplay, etc. configurable via props unless the project already hardcodes them.
- Use proper typing (TS/Dart if applicable).
- Production-ready.
- No console logs.`;
---

<Layout title="IconTree - AI Prompt">
  <div class="doc-content doc-content-wide prompt-shell">
    <div class="doc-nav">
      <a href="/" class="back-link">&lt; Back</a>
    </div>

    <section class="doc-hero">
      <span class="doc-kicker">AI Prompt</span>
      <h1>One Prompt to Use IconTree</h1>
      <p class="doc-lead">
        This prompt is for adding IconTree icons into an existing app, not for building a new icon library.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="prompt-card">
      <h3>Prompt</h3>
      <p>Copy this prompt into your AI tool when you want it to build or integrate IconTree correctly.</p>
      <pre><code>{promptText}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="lang-grid" aria-label="Prompt guidance">
      <article class="lang-card">
        <h3>Structure</h3>
        <p>
          The prompt tells the AI three things clearly: use the existing app, choose API or manual mode, and only
          write integration code for that app feature.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="lang-card">
        <h3>How to Add It</h3>
        <p>
          Paste the prompt first, then add one short line about your stack and target screen, like “Use React on the
          settings page” or “Use Android Kotlin in the onboarding screen”.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-callout">
      <p><strong>Example add-on lines</strong></p>
      <ul class="prompt-list">
        <li><code>Use React and Tailwind.</code></li>
        <li><code>Use Android Kotlin with a LottieAnimationView.</code></li>
        <li><code>Use manual local JSON files, not remote API calls.</code></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script>
    (function() {
      const preBlocks = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.doc-content pre')) as HTMLElement[];

      preBlocks.forEach((pre: HTMLElement) => {
        const btn = document.createElement('button');
        btn.className = 'copy-snippet-btn';
        btn.textContent = 'Copy';
        btn.type = 'button';
        pre.style.position = 'relative';
        pre.appendChild(btn);

        btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const code = pre.querySelector('code');
          const text = code?.textContent || '';

          navigator.clipboard.writeText(text).then(() => {
            btn.textContent = 'Copied!';
            btn.classList.add('copied');

            setTimeout(() => {
              btn.textContent = 'Copy';
              btn.classList.remove('copied');
            }, 2000);
          });
        });
      });
    })();
  </script>
</Layout>
